passages.text: AFL | Boeing Company (Seth M. Seifman, CFA) (BA, OW, PT \(\) 251.00\$

We met Boeing CEO Kelly Ortberg last night for an update just over a year after he took the helm. The story here remains one of execution and the progress we have seen this year, combined with mgmt's plans for the future, leave us encouraged. 737 and 787 rates should increase gradually, with the path to 42 on 737 looking clear. Defense challenges remain but BDS has restructured programs and the days of massive charges should be behind us.
BILL (Tien- tsin Huang, CFA) (BILL, OW, PT \(\) 55.00\$

BILL managed to clear and set a reasonable bar amid low expectations for 4Q and FY26 guidance. F4Q came in ahead on revenue and profits on better TPV and take rates, partially helped by potential pull forward of high- yielding spend ahead of tariffs given QTD trends. Even with SMB discretionary spending competing with tariff costs, F1Q guidance appears reasonable, bracketing consensus and consistent with typical seasonality, which we view as a victory for the stock.
NVIDIA Corporation (Harlan Sur) (NVDA, OW, PT \(\) 215.00\$
Blackwell/Blackwell Ultra Ramp and Networking Strength Drive Solid Results/Guidance; H20 Upside Still Likely in the Cards, in Our View; Reit OW

NVIDIA reported solid Jul- Qtr revenue of \(\) 46.7B\(above ours/consensus estimates of\) \ \(45.0B /\) 46.2B), a \(\sim 6\%\) Q/Q improvement, aided in part by \(\sim\) 650MM of H20 revenue to a non- China customer (with H20 having been stripped out of Jul- Qtr expectations) but primarily driven by \(11 - 12\%\) Q/Q growth in Blackwell GPU compute revenue (B200/GB200 and B300/GB300) to \(\sim\) 26BJPMe) and sharply higher networking revenue (+46% Q/Q) as the team benefits from higher networking content (scale- up) in their rack scale systems.
CwdStrike (Brian Essex, CFA) (CRWD, OW, PT \(\) 500.00\$

Solid 2Q beat with better than expected NNARR acceleration into the back half of the year. CRWD delivered better- than- expected results for 2Q with revenue, ARR, profitability, and FCF all ahead of consensus estimates. ARR performance was supported by traction with Cloud, Next- Gen Identity and Next- Gen SIEM which together accounted for more than \(\) 1.56b\(in ARR. Underlying growth was supported by strong Falcon Flex traction with more than 1,000 customers now on Flex.
HP Inc (Samik Chatterjee, CFA) (HPQ, OW, PT \(\) 30.00)\$

In our view, HPQ will push the wall of investor worries relative to a potential slowdown in the PC market (following a pull-forward led by tariff worries) as well as concerns relative to delivering to robust Print margins in the face of higher competition, with its latest F3Q results managing to deliver on both fronts as well as keep its full-year outlook intact following the lowered expectations last quarter.
NetApp, Inc. (Samik Chatterjee, CFA) (NTAP, OW, PT \(\) 130.00)\$

NetApp delivered to its own forecasts relative to both revenue and margins in F1Q, but given typical management conservatism early in the year, the company reiterated its full-year guidance. While within the earnings results investors might be concerned about the modest gross margin miss to consensus expectations, the product-mix led deviation from the midpoint of the guide is only modest (71.1% vs. guidance of 71%-72% and consensus of 71.5%), and additionally not material enough to lead the management team to change its expectations for the full year (FY26); although the reiterated gross margin guide for the full year is likely helped by better outlook for Public Cloud gross margins where the company is raising its long-term gross margin expectations from 75%-80% prior to 80%-85%.
**ChargePoint** (Bill Peterson) (CHPT, UW, PT \(\) 9.00)\$

We model 2Q revenue of \(\) 97M\((vs. consensus\)\\(96M\) and guide \(\) 90-100M)\(and EBITDA loss of\)\\(24M\) (vs. consensus \(\) 21M). Our revenue estimates contemplate 2Q hardware revenue remaining fairly flat with 1Q, despite it being a historically stronger quarter due to seasonality, taking into account the mixed impacts of potential pre-buying in the first half of this year ahead of anticipated tax credit phase-outs or tariffs, which could result in incremental deliveries landing in 2Q, or, customers doubling down on pausing new orders due to a worse EV sales and market penetration outlook in the years to come.
